          If you're unsure whether your child is a late talker or has a delay, here's a practical approach:
        </p>
        <p class="text-warmgray-600 mb-4">
          <strong>1. Trust your gut.</strong> You know your child. If something feels off, it's worth exploring—even if everyone tells you to "just wait."
        </p>
        <p class="text-warmgray-600 mb-4">
          <strong>2. Get a hearing test.</strong> Rule out hearing issues first. Even mild or intermittent hearing loss can affect speech development.
        </p>
        <p class="text-warmgray-600 mb-4">
          <strong>3. Consider an evaluation.</strong> A speech-language pathologist can assess where your child is and whether intervention would help. An evaluation doesn't commit you to anything—it gives you information.
        </p>
        <p class="text-warmgray-600">
          <strong>4. Don't wait too long.</strong> If your child is 18+ months with very few words, or 24+ months without two-word combinations, it's reasonable to at least have a conversation with a professional.
        </p>
